# Known `inArray()` bind lists the guard flags but that are safe.
#
# Format matches check-d1-100col-joins.allowlist: one `repo-relative/path.ts`
# per line, optionally `:<line>` to pin a single site. `#` starts a comment.
#
# Adding an entry accepts a latent 500. Prefer fixing the site:
#   reads  → chunkedInArray(xs, (batch) => …inArray(col, batch)…)
#   writes → for (const batch of chunkIds(xs)) { … }
# both from @takemetothefair/utils.
#
# Add NEW entries only with an explicit reason (and an issue link if it's a
# deferred fix rather than a genuine exception).
#
# ── The citation supersede-prior pattern (OPE-241) ───────────────────────
#
# All five sites below share one shape:
#
#     const priorActive = await db.select().from(eventDataCitations)
#       .where(and(sameKeyFilter(event_id, field_name, year),
#                  eq(eventDataCitations.state, "active")));
#     …update(…).where(inArray(eventDataCitations.id, priorActive.map(r => r.id)))
#
# The guard flags them because that select has no `.limit()`. They are safe for
# a reason the scanner cannot see: the rows are scoped to ONE
# (event_id, field_name, year) key with state='active', and the supersede logic
# itself maintains "at most one active citation per key" — the surrounding code
# reads `priorActive[0]` on exactly that assumption. So the list is ~1 element,
# not a row-count-scaled list, and chunking would add noise without removing
# risk.
#
# If that invariant is ever broken (a writer inserting 'active' without
# superseding), these become genuinely unbounded — fix the writer, then drop
# these entries in favour of chunking.
